# Leash Constitution

## Core Rules

1. Safety gates are non-negotiable. Every motor command passes through deadman, estop, soft-odometry-limit, and physical-actuation-gate before reaching hardware.
2. Feature-gating is mandatory for hardware-specific adapters. The Waveshare UGV adapter must not compile unless enabled (`--features waveshare-ugv`). Physical profile refuses to start without `--allow-physical-actuation` or `LEASH_ALLOW_PHYSICAL_ACTUATION=1`.
3. The harness runtime is a library first. CLI and MCP server are thin shells around the `Harness` struct.
4. Pilot token authorization. Drive commands require a valid pilot token with TTL. Tokens expire. Untokened drive is configurable but defaults on for sim.
5. Deadman switch. If no drive command arrives within `deadman_ms` (default 400ms), motors are automatically stopped. This is a runtime safety gate, not config-level.
6. Smoke tests gate every release. MCP, HTTP, and physical-gate smoke tests must pass before any publish.
7. LLM agents operate through MCP only. No HTTP endpoint accepts unauthenticated commands — MCP is the agent interface.
8. Sim-safe by default. The harness must run without hardware present. CI, demos, and smoke tests require zero physical robots. Sim profile logs commands instead of actuating.
9. Explicit physical actuation gate. Physical profiles (waveshare-ugv) require `allow_physical_actuation: true` in config or `LEASH_ALLOW_PHYSICAL_ACTUATION=1` env var.
10. Module graph with typed streams (planned). Every module declares inputs, outputs, lifecycle, and health. Streams are typed and validated at graph construction time.
11. Replay determinism (planned). Recorded sessions must reproduce identical telemetry when replayed against the same inputs. Replay is a safety and debugging primitive.
12. Transport abstraction (planned). Module communication works identically across in-process, cross-process, and network transports. No module knows its peer's location.
13. Pawprint catalog (planned). Every demo, robot config, and replay scenario is a versioned, runnable pawprint. No ad-hoc wiring at runtime.
14. Generic operating surface. Leash targets typed modules, reusable run targets, replay, telemetry, local-first execution, and MCP-native agent integration without binding the roadmap to another project.
